tes inter-segment capacity sharing between GEO and LEO constellations. |\n| **Currency** | USD | EUR (requiring FX conversion, introducing ~1–2% variability depending on rate selected) |\n| **Seasonality** | Annualizing a single quarter (Q1) may not capture seasonal patterns in subscriber acquisition or enterprise contract timing. | Annualizing H1 (Jul–Dec) may similarly misrepresent full-year trends, particularly if H2 benefits from seasonal enterprise/government budget cycles. |\n| **Backlog Disclosure** | The S-1 does not appear to disclose a comparable backlog figure for Connectivity. | Eutelsat discloses a ~€1 billion OneWeb backlog, providing forward visibility not available from SpaceX\'s filing. |\n\n---\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nStarlink\'s Connectivity segment generates approximately **50× the annualized revenue** of Eutelsat\'s OneWeb LEO segment (~$13.0 billion vs. ~$260 million). This gap reflects Starlink\'s far greater commercial maturity: a 9,600-satellite constellation serving 164 markets with diversified consumer, enterprise, and government revenue streams, versus OneWeb\'s 618-satellite first-generation constellation still in early commercial ramp with a partner-dependent distribution model.\n\nHowever, the precision of this comparison is limited by non-aligned fiscal periods, differing segment definitions (particularly the treatment of hardware revenue), the recast consolidation scope of SpaceX\'s S-1, and the absence of comparable sub-segment granularity in Eutelsat\'s disclosures. The ~50× figure should be interpreted as an order-of-magnitude indicator of relative commercial scale rather than a precise like-for-like benchmark.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.ad-hoc-news.de/boerse/news/ueberblick/eutelsat-